        <hr class="col-3 col-md-5 mb-3 mx-auto" />

        <p class="p-4 display-6 text-center mx-auto col-lg-8 col-10">
          A few things to know before diving into the code...
        </p>

        <div class="row g-5">
          <div class="col-md-4">
            <h3>Site</h3>
            <p>
              The scaffold command installs a self-contained web server as a sub
              package of a Golang project. eg...
            </p>
            <p>
              <code>[my-go-prj]$ good scaffold ./portal</code>
            </p>
            <p>
              Embedded within the codebase, it can make use of internal server
              code and configuration, this reduces the overhead of maintaining
              an integrated GUI.
            </p>
            <h5>Read the code</h5>
            <p>
              The scaffold code is self documenting. After a quick read through,
              you should have a sense of how to modify and re-purpose it to suit
              your needs.
            </p>
            <p>
              Beyond code, guides can be found in the
              <em>[site]/docs</em> directory in your scaffold.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="col-md-4">
            <h3>Pages</h3>
            <p>
              Top-level sections are organized into pages, each with it's own
              routing config for page endpoints.
            </p>

            <p>
              An app can have as many top level pages as you wish. They are
              independent by default; use your refactoring skills to control
              duplication as your site grows.
            </p>

            <h5>Resources:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>
                A <code>service.Env</code> singleton is initialized during
                startup and passed to handlers.
              </li>
              <li>
                Each page has a private <code>resources{}</code> struct for
                request-scoped data.
              </li>
              <li>
                The <code>[site]/page</code> package is the destination for
                shared templates and request helpers.
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              App services and resources are injected to handlers using
              straightforward, type-safe function closures.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="col-md-4">
            <h3>Routes</h3>
            <p>
              Routing is configured with a TOML file in each page directory. The
              <code>good routes [page_pkg]</code> command generates the
              <em>routes.go</em> file with plumbing for page endpoints.
            </p>

            <h5>Route Map</h5>
            <p>
              The <code>routemap.toml</code> config file outlines the layout
              hierarchy for a page and map: paths, templates and handlers to
              define HTML endpoints.
            </p>

            <h4>Role of code generation:</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Create the initial scaffold</li>
              <li>Add new pages</li>
              <li>Update page routes</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              <strong>gen.go</strong> files appear in the appropriate places so
              that a recursive, <code>go generate &lt;site&gt;/...</code>,
              command will take care of code-gen tasks.
            </p>
          </div>

          <hr class="col-3 col-md-5 mb-3 mx-auto" />

          <div class="row mt-5">
            <div class="col col-md-6 px-4 mb-5">
              <h4 class="mb-3"><strong>ðŸ“ˆ next step,</strong> add a page</h4>
